Certainly! Let's consider an example using Spring Boot, Redis, and Bucket4j to implement rate limiting for the given scenario:

1. Start by adding the necessary dependencies to your `pom.xml` file:

```xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>io.github.bucket4j</groupId>
    <artifactId>bucket4j-core</artifactId>
    <version>4.13.1</version>
</dependency>
<dependency>
    <groupId>io.github.bucket4j</groupId>
    <artifactId>bucket4j-redis</artifactId>
    <version>4.13.1</version>
</dependency>
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.springframework.boot</groupId>
    <artifactId>spring-boot-starter-data-redis</artifactId>
</dependency>
```

2. Configure Redis in your `application.properties` file, adding the necessary Redis connection properties:

```properties
spring.redis.host=<redis-host>
spring.redis.port=<redis-port>
# Add more properties if required: password, connection timeout, etc.
```

3. Create a `RateLimitService` class to encapsulate the rate limiting logic:

```java
@Service
public class RateLimitService {
    private final RedissonClient redissonClient;
    private final Map<String, RateLimiter> rateLimiters;

    public RateLimitService(RedissonClient redissonClient) {
        this.redissonClient = redissonClient;
        this.rateLimiters = new HashMap<>();
    }

    public void applyRateLimit(String api, int maxCalls, Duration duration) {
        RateLimiter rateLimiter = rateLimiters.getOrDefault(api, createRateLimiter(api, maxCalls, duration));
        rateLimiter.tryConsume();
    }

    private RateLimiter createRateLimiter(String api, int maxCalls, Duration duration) {
        RRateLimiter rRateLimiter = redissonClient.getRateLimiter(api);
        rRateLimiter.trySetRate(RateType.OVERALL, maxCalls, duration.toSeconds());
        RateLimiter rateLimiter = Bucket4j.from(rRateLimiter);
        rateLimiters.put(api, rateLimiter);
        return rateLimiter;
    }
}
```

4. Inject the `RateLimitService` in your API controller and apply the rate limits as follows:

```java
@RestController
public class ApiController {
    private final RateLimitService rateLimitService;

    public ApiController(RateLimitService rateLimitService) {
        this.rateLimitService = rateLimitService;
    }

    @GetMapping("/api1")
    public ResponseEntity<String> api1() {
        rateLimitService.applyRateLimit("api1", 100, Duration.ofHours(1));
        // Rest of the logic for API 1
        return ResponseEntity.ok("API 1 success");
    }

    @GetMapping("/api2")
    public ResponseEntity<String> api2() {
        rateLimitService.applyRateLimit("api2", 200, Duration.ofHours(1));
        // Rest of the logic for API 2
        return ResponseEntity.ok("API 2 success");
    }

    // Add more API methods and rate limits as required
}
```

This example demonstrates how to use Bucket4j and Redis to apply rate limiting for two APIs, "api1" and "api2". The `RateLimitService` class keeps track of rate limiters for each API and applies the rate limits using the `applyRateLimit` method.

Make sure you have a Redis server running and properly configured in the `application.properties` file.

Please note that this is just a basic implementation. You may need to adjust and enhance it according to your specific requirements.

I hope this helps you get started with implementing rate limiting in your Spring Boot application using Bucket4j and Redis! Let me know if you have any further questions.

No, in the current implementation, activating another pod will not automatically synchronize the rate limits and keep track of the previously made calls. Each pod would have its own rate limiter instance associated with the specific API. 

To achieve centralized rate limiting and keep track of the calls across multiple pods, you would need to employ a shared backend, such as Redis, to maintain and synchronize the rate limit state. Bucket4j provides integration with Redis, allowing you to achieve this.

Here's an updated approach using Bucket4j and Redis to address your requirement:

1. Modify the `RateLimitService` to use a shared Redis backend for rate limiting:

```java
@Service
public class RateLimitService {
    private final RedissonClient redissonClient;

    public RateLimitService(RedissonClient redissonClient) {
        this.redissonClient = redissonClient;
    }

    public void applyRateLimit(String api, int maxCalls, Duration duration) {
        RRateLimiter rateLimiter = redissonClient.getRateLimiter(api);
        rateLimiter.trySetRate(RateType.OVERALL, maxCalls, duration.toSeconds());
        if (!rateLimiter.tryAcquire()) {
            throw new RateLimitExceededException("Rate limit exceeded for API: " + api);
        }
    }
}
```

2. Modify the configuration for Redis in the `application.properties` file and ensure that all pods connect to the same Redis instance:

```properties
spring.redis.host=<redis-host>
spring.redis.port=<redis-port>
```

With this updated implementation, all pods will use the same Redis rate limiter instance to enforce rate limits and keep track of the calls made across multiple pods. If a request exceeds the rate limit, the `tryAcquire()` method will throw a `RateLimitExceededException`, and you can handle it accordingly.

It's important to note that when using a shared Redis backend, you may need to handle cases where the Redis connection fails or is lost. You can add appropriate error-handling logic to handle these scenarios gracefully.

I hope this clarifies how to achieve centralized rate limiting and keep track of calls across multiple pods using Bucket4j and Redis. Let me know if you have any further questions!

